
## 1ï¸âƒ£ What is Sliding Window (Core Idea)

### Concept

A **window** is a subrange `[l â€¦ r]` that moves over data.

Instead of recalculating everything:

* You **reuse previous work**
* Add one element
* Remove one element

ğŸ“Œ Used for **subarray / substring** problems.

---

## 2ï¸âƒ£ Why Sliding Window Exists (Optimization Logic)

### Brute Force

* Check all subarrays
* Time â†’ **O(nÂ²)**

### Sliding Window

* Each element added once
* Each element removed once

â±ï¸ Time â†’ **O(n)**

ğŸ“Œ This is a massive improvement.

---

## 3ï¸âƒ£ Fixed Size Sliding Window

### When to Use

* Window size `k` is **given**

### Template

```python
window_sum = sum(arr[:k])

for i in range(k, n):
    window_sum += arr[i]      # add new
    window_sum -= arr[i-k]    # remove old
```

ğŸ“Œ Window size never changes.

---

## 4ï¸âƒ£ Variable Size Sliding Window

### When to Use

* Condition based window size
* Example: sum â‰¤ k, distinct count, etc.

### Template

```python
l = 0
for r in range(n):
    add(arr[r])

    while condition_invalid:
        remove(arr[l])
        l += 1
```

ğŸ“Œ Window **expands and shrinks dynamically**.

---

## 5ï¸âƒ£ Relationship: Two Pointers vs Sliding Window

| Two Pointers  | Sliding Window      |
| ------------- | ------------------- |
| Generic       | Specialized         |
| Any movement  | Structured movement |
| Pair problems | Subarray problems   |

ğŸ“Œ Sliding window is **disciplined two pointers**.

---

## 6ï¸âƒ£ Common Mistakes to Avoid

âŒ Resetting window every time
âŒ Nested loops
âŒ Forgetting to remove left element
âŒ Using extra space unnecessarily

âœ… Each element must:

* enter window once
* leave window once

